subsection.p:
In order to understand how big something is, we need to know what scale we are using.  For example, Your thumb is about an inch across, but your foot is about a foot long.  Both have the amount 1. but the unit is different.  In this sense, 1+1 might not equal 2.

                         1 \unit{ft} + 1 \unit{ft} \amp = 2 \unit{ft} 
                         1 \unit{in} + 1 \unit{ft} \amp \ne 2 \unit{??} 

                        For the second line, you need to convert the units:
                         1 \unit{in} + 1 \unit{ft} = 1 \unit{in} + 1 \unit{ft}\convert{12\unit{in}}{1\unit{ft}} = 1 \unit{in} + 12 \unit{in} = 13\unit{in} 
                        because we need to be speaking about the same thing.  You have all had the experience of a miscommunication when you thought you were speaking about the same thing, but later found out you each meant something different.

subsubsection.p:
If \vec A = 3 \vec B, then this is true for each component.
A_x \amp = 3 B_x A_y \amp = 3 B_y A_z \amp = 3 B_z
This can also be written in two different ways: \vect{A_x}{+A_y}{+A_z} \ = \ 3 \left( \vect{B_x}{+B_y}{+B_z} \right) \ = \ \vect{(3B_x)}{+(3B_y)}{+(3B_z)}

convention.p:
This text will use fast to indicate moving with a large speed (to be distinguished from quick).

				\text{fast}
				refers to moving with a large speed (to be distinguished from quick)

This text will use quick to indicate moving with a large acceleration (to be distinguished from fast).

				\text{quick}
				refers to moving with a large acceleration (to be distinguished from fast)

subsection.p:
The technical term acceleration means changing the velocity, which refers to either speeding up (colloquially acceleration) or slowing down (colloquially deceleration) or changing the direction (colloquially turning).

				\text{acceleration}
				refers to the general idea of changing your motion (velocity), meaning either speeding up (colloquially acceleration) or slowing down (colloquially deceleration) or changing the direction (colloquially turning)

hint.p:
The first thing we should do is notice what information is given to us and make sure that everything is in consistent units.  I will convert everything to SI units.

                                         v_i & = 55.0\unitfrac{mi}{hr}
                                                \convert{1609 \unit{ft}}{1.0000 \unit{mi}}_{4\unit{sig}}
                                                \convert{1\unit{hr}}{3600\unit{s}}_\mathrm{exact} = \sigfrac{24.5}{8}{m}{s} 
                                         \Delta x & = 2.25\unit{mi} \convert{1609 \unit{ft}}{1.0000 \unit{mi}}_{4\unit{sig}}
                                                = \sig{362}{0.3}{m} = \sig{3.62}{0\ten{3}}{m}

The first thing we should do is notice what information is given to us and make sure that everything is in consistent units.  I will convert everything to SI units.

                                         v_i & = 55.0\unitfrac{mi}{hr}
                                                \convert{1609 \unit{ft}}{1.0000 \unit{mi}}_{4\unit{sig}}
                                                \convert{1\unit{hr}}{3600\unit{s}}_\mathrm{exact} = \sigfrac{24.5}{8}{m}{s} 
                                         \Delta x & = 2.25\unit{mi}
                                                \convert{1609 \unit{ft}}{1.0000 \unit{mi}}_{4\unit{sig}} = \sig{362}{0.3}{m} = \sig{3.62}{0\ten{3}}{m}

The first thing we should do is notice what information is given to us and make sure that everything is in consistent units.  I will convert everything to metric.

                                                 3\unit{rungs}  & = 3.00\unit{ft} \convert{0.3048 \unit m}{1.00000\unit{ft}} = 0.\sig{914}{4}{m} 
                                                 6\unit{rungs}  & = 6.00\unit{ft} \convert{0.3048 \unit m}{1.00000\unit{ft}} = \sig{1.82}{9}{m} 
                                                 11\unit{rungs}  & = 11.00\unit{ft} \convert{0.3048 \unit m}{1.00000\unit{ft}} = \sig{3.35}{3}{m}

solution.p:
To find the acceleration in each case, we can solve v_f^2 = v_i^2 + 2 a \, \Delta x for the acceleration:

                                                 a_3 & = \frac{(4.23\unitfrac ms)^2 - (0 \unitfrac ms)^2}{2(0.\sig{914}{4}{m})}
                                                        \ = \ \sigfrac{9.83}{1}{m}{s^2} 
                                                 a_6 & = \frac{(6.00\unitfrac ms)^2 - (0 \unitfrac ms)^2}{2(\sig{1.82}{9}{m})}
                                                        \ = \ \sigfrac{9.84}{1}{m}{s^2} 
                                                 a_11 & = \frac{(8.11\unitfrac ms)^2 - (0 \unitfrac ms)^2}{2(\sig{3.35}{3}{m})}
                                                        \ = \ \sigfrac{9.80}{8}{m}{s^2} 

                                        Notice that these have some variation due to the rounding.  It turns out that the variation in the value of acceleration depends on the composition of the earth in your location as well as your altitude above sea-level.  That will be discussed in detail in , for simplicity we will assume (by ) that all objects accelerate at the rate of 9.81\unitfrac{m}{s^2} when they are solely under the influence of gravity.

hint.p:
We can find the time of flight (not useful) and the velocity when the ball reaches the ceiling:

                                         v_\mathrm{top} & = \sqrt{ v_\mathrm{bot}^2 + 2 a \, \Delta x} 
                                         v_\mathrm{top} & = \sqrt{ (+5.00\unitfrac ms)^2 + 2 (-9.81\unitfrac{m}{s^2})(+1.00\unit{m})} 
                                         v_\mathrm{top} & = +\sigfrac{2.31}{9}{m}{s} 

                                Note: When you take the square root, you have to decide if you should take the positive sign or the negative sign.  In this case, the ball is still moving upwards, so we choose the positive sign.

The fourth stage, like the second, is while the ball moves from the ceiling down to \studentC's hand. During this portion of the motion we know that the velocity at the bottom (final) is \vec v_\mathrm{bot} = -1.67\unitfrac ms \jhat, that it travels \Delta \vec x = -1.00\unit{m} \jhat, and that (because it is in freefall) it is accelerating at \vec a_g = -9.81\unitfrac{m}{s^2} \jhat. We can find the time of flight (not useful) and the velocity when the ball leaves the ceiling (initial), solving v_\mathrm{bot}^2 = v_\mathrm{top}^2 + 2 a \, \Delta x for v_\mathrm{top}:
v_\mathrm{top} & = \sqrt{ v_\mathrm{bot}^2 - 2 a \, \Delta x} v_\mathrm{top} & = \sqrt{ (-1.67\unitfrac ms)^2 - 2 (-9.81\unitfrac{m}{s^2})(+1.00\unit{m})} v_\mathrm{top} & = -\sigfrac{4.73}{4}{m}{s}
Note: When you take the square root, you have to decide if you should take the positive sign or the negative sign. In this case, the ball is now moving downwards, so we choose the negative sign.

solution.p:
Now that we have the velocities immediately before (from ) and after (from ) the collision with the ceiling, we can find the acceleration:
                                                 a = \frac{v_f-v_i}{\Delta t}
                                                        = \frac{(-\sigfrac{4.73}{4}{m}{s})-(+\sigfrac{2.31}{9}{m}{s})}{(0.142\unit s)}
                                                        = -\sigfrac{28.0}{9}{m}{s^2} \,\jhat 
                                        Notice that the acceleration is negative because the ball went from going up to going down.

