solution.p:
How are what-we-know and what-we-want related?
                                The forces acting on any body are related by static translational equilibrium

                                 x: \hspace{.5cm} 0 \amp = \cancel{0}{F_{gx}} + \cancelto{0}{F_{Nfx}}{0} + F_{ffx} + F_{Nwx} + \cancelto{0}{F_{fwx}} 
                                 y: \hspace{.5cm} 0 \amp = F_{gy} + F_{Nfy} + \cancelto{0}{F_{ffy}} + \cancelto{0}{F_{Nwy}} + F_{fwy} 

                                and static rotational equilibrium, assuming the pivot point is at the ground, and using the relationship F_f=\mu F_N, we find

                                 0 \amp = \tau_{g} + \cancelto{0}{\tau_{Nf}} + \cancelto{0}{\tau_{ff}} + \tau_{Nw} + \tau_{fw} 
                                 0 \amp = \left[ F_g \frac{l}{2} \sin 14.5^\circ \right] + \left[ - F_{Nw} l \sin(75.5^\circ) \right] + \left[ - F_{fw} l \sin(14.5^\circ) \right] 
                                 F_{Nw} \amp = \left[ F_g \frac{l}{2} \sin 14.5^\circ \right] / \left[  l \sin(75.5^\circ) + \mu_w l \sin(14.5^\circ) \right]

Solution to the example:
                                When we worry about significant figures,

                                 F_{Nw} \amp = \frac{\left[ (\sig{222}{.7}{N})(\txtfrac{1}{2}) (0.\sig{250}{4}{}) \right]}
                                                {\left[  (0.\sig{968}{2}{}) + (0.19) (0.\sig{250}{4}{}) \right]}
                                        \ = \ \frac{\left[ (\sig{27.8}{8}{N})\right]}{\left[  (0.\sig{968}{2}{}) + (0.0\sig{47}{6}{}) \right]} 
                                 F_{Nw} \amp = \frac{\left[ (\sig{27.8}{8}{N})\right]}{\left[  (\sig{1.015}{7}{}) \right]}
                                        \ = \ \sig{27.4}{4}{N} 
                                 F_{fw,\mathrm{max}} \amp = (0.19)(\sig{27.4}{4}{N}) \ = \ \sig{5.2}{15}{N} 
                                 F_{Nf} \amp = F_g - F_{fw} = (\sig{222}{.7}{N})-(\sig{5.2}{15}{N}) \ = \ \sig{217}{.5}{N} 
                                 F_{ff,\mathrm{max}} \amp = (0.31)(\sig{217}{.5}{N}) \ = \ \sig{672}{.4}{N} 

                                Since F_{ff} >F_{Nw}, the friction is sufficient to hold the ladder in place, as assumed.

The normal force from the wall is the only force to the right.  The frictional force from the floor is the only force to the left.  Using the calculations in , we notice that

                                 F_{Nw} \amp = \sig{163}{.9}{N} 
                                 F_{fw,\mathrm{max}} \amp = (0.19)(\sig{163}{.9}{N}) \ = \ \sig{31}{.14}{N} 
                                 F_{Nf} \amp = \sig{1074}{.4}{N} 
                                 F_{ff,\mathrm{max}} \amp = \sig{333}{.0}{N} \gt \sig{163}{.9}{N} 

                                The frictional force with the floor can support a normal force from the wall of 333\unit N, but the normal force is only 164\unit N so the ladder stays in place.  In fact it is possible to compute the smallest coefficient of floor-friction that will keep the ladder in place:
                                \mu_\mathrm{min} = 0.\sig{152}{56}{}.

The normal force from the wall is the only force to the right.  The frictional force from the floor is the only force to the left.  Using the calculations in , we notice that

                                 F_{Nw} \amp = \sig{108}{.97}{N} 
                                 F_{fw,\mathrm{max}} \amp = (0.19)(\sig{108}{.97}{N}) \ = \ \sig{20}{.70}{N} 
                                 F_{Nf} \amp = \sig{1084}{.9}{N} 
                                 F_{ff,\mathrm{max}} \amp = \sig{336}{.3}{N} \gt \sig{108}{.97}{N} 

                                The frictional force with the floor can support a normal force from the wall of 336\unit N, but the normal force is only 109\unit N so the ladder stays in place.  In fact it is possible to compute the smallest coefficient of floor-friction that will keep the ladder in place:
                                \mu_\mathrm{min} = 0.\sig{100}{45}{}

If, hypothetically, \mu_w = 0, then

                                 F_{Nw} \amp = \sig{114}{.3}{N} 
                                 F_{fw,\mathrm{max}} \amp = 0 \unit N 
                                 F_{Nf} \amp = \sig{1105}{.6}{N} 
                                 F_{ff,\mathrm{max}} \amp = \sig{342}{.7}{N} \gt \sig{114}{.3}{N} 

                                The frictional force with the floor can support a normal force from the wall of 336\unit N, but the normal force is only 109\unit N so the ladder stays in place.  In fact it is possible to compute the smallest coefficient of floor-friction that will keep the ladder in place:
